She'd look after two pigs, we'd feed them. Three times a day. And we used to keep one - for our own - use, and sell the other you see. Used to send the other to people in Neath - who mother came to know, and used to sell - the flitch - after it wa
s cured. After it was cured do you see. Used to kill the two pigs and - cure the two - and cure the two, we had - they used to hang - hanging up in the kitchen, hang the - sides you call 'em, to - cure 'em see. To dry out as it were after being in salt. O
h
 she was good at that. And there was an aunt - Mrs Morgan - well this mother - my mother's sister, she was a good aunt to cure - allti you call it, allti cig, salt the meat. She - she - she - I never - I never see her failing. We had a large stone slab - 
in this back kitchen in this lean-to, and she used to - salt - the two - the - the two }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3696877\charrsid10955930 fitches}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13139658\charrsid10955930 
 there see, for - so many weeks you see. And then bring 'em into the kitchen then and hang 'em up in the kitchen. We had - we - we were for weeks - ducking under t
his -'cos they were there to - to cure - to dry out again. Dry out you see after the salt see. Oh very - very - very interesting to look back at it now. Look back sometimes.
